Certainly! Below is an HTML file that functions as a simple web application. It displays 10 random words from multiple languages and includes embedded CSS for styling and JavaScript to generate the random words.

You can copy and paste this code into a `.html` file and open it in your web browser to see it in action.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Random Words App</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #f0f0f0;
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            height: 100vh;
            margin: 0;
        }
        .container {
            background-color: white;
            padding: 20px;
            border-radius: 8px;
            box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
            text-align: center;
        }
        h1 {
            margin-bottom: 20px;
        }
        .words {
            font-size: 1.5em;
            color: #333;
        }
        button {
            padding: 10px 20px;
            font-size: 1em;
            border: none;
            background-color: #007bff;
            color: white;
            border-radius: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
            margin-top: 20px;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <h1>Random Words</h1>
        <div class="words" id="wordList"></div>
        <button onclick="generateWords()">Generate Random Words</button>
    </div>

    <script>
        const words = [
            'Hola',  // Spanish for Hello
            'Bonjour', // French for Good Morning
            'Ciao', // Italian for Hi
            'Привет', // Russian for Hello
            '你好', // Chinese for Hello
            'こんにちは', // Japanese for Hello
            '안녕하세요', // Korean for Hello
            'שלום', // Hebrew for Peace/Hello
            'हैलो', // Hindi for Hello
            'Olá', // Portuguese for Hello
        ];

        function generateWords() {
            const shuffledWords = words.sort(() => 0.5 - Math.random());
            const selectedWords = shuffledWords.slice(0, 10);
            document.getElementById('wordList').innerText = selectedWords.join(', ');
        }

        // Generate words on initial load
        window.onload = generateWords;
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### How it Works
1. **HTML Structure**: The HTML contains a title, a container for displaying random words, and a button to generate new words.
2. **CSS Styles**: The CSS styles enhance the visual appearance of the app, making it more user-friendly and aesthetically pleasing.
3. **JavaScript Functionality**:
   - An array of words in different languages is defined.
   - The `generateWords()` function randomly shuffles this array, selects 10 words, and displays them in the container.
   - The function is called on window load to populate the words initially.

Now you can save this code in an HTML file and open it in a web browser to use your random words app!
